{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Masubia |population = |region1 = [[Caprivi strip]], [[Namibia]] |pop1 = |ref1 = <ref name=Bwinkuhane>{{cite news |url=http://www.newera.com.na/articles/53348/Thousands-celebrate-Bwinkuhane-Bwetu |title=Thousands celebrate Bwinkuhane Bwetu |last=Sanzila |first=George |date=29 July 2013 |work=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]]}}</ref> |region2 = [[Zambia]] |pop2 = |ref2 = <ref name=Bwinkuhane/> |region3 = [[Botswana]] |pop3 = |ref3 = <ref name=Bwinkuhane/> |region4 = |pop4 = |ref4 = |region5 = |pop5 = |ref5 = |region6 = |pop6 = |ref6 = |region7 = |pop7 = |ref7 = |region8 = |pop8 = |ref8 = |region9 = |pop9 = |ref9 = |region10 = |pop10 = |ref10 = |languages = |religions = Traditional ancestor worship, Christianity |related = |footnotes = }}
The '''Masubia''' are the largest tribe in [[Caprivi Strip]] whose traditional authority (''kuta'') is based in [[Bukalo]].<ref>http://www.caprivi.biz/people.html</ref>
==History== They Masubia originate from Central Africa. In Southern Africa they first settled in the [[Goha Hills]] of Botswana. Due to the tribal conflicts in Botswana,{{when|date=July 2013}} they moved to the great Caprivi. In that region they erected their headquarters in Bukalo under the leadership of the first Masubia king, [[King Sanjo]].<ref>http://arroukatchee.fr/eng/namibia/people/caprivians.html{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The invasion of the [[Lozi people|Lozi]] of Zambia and the [[Kololo]] of South Africa between the 17th and 18th century led to the current blend of cultures, language and traditions.
==Ways of life== They live off farming and gathering, hunting and fishing. The women are responsible for farming activities while the men deal with the hunting and fishing. Their staple food is hard porridge ''(inkoko)'' with fish or sour milk ''(masanza)''.{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}}
==Villages== The Masubia villages are called ''minzi''. The homes consist of huts made up of a mud wall and thatch roof or houses with concrete walls and sheet metal roofs. The huts are surrounded by a reed fence known as ''ilapa''. The villages often consist of 15 to 30 families.{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}}.
Nkuhaane village names are given in accordance or with consideration to major life events that took place or were believed to have taken place in that area such as <ref>"ciwongo ca masaku" an isolated peace of land which was and is still believed to be a place where ghosts live/d.</ref> the main villages of the nkuhaane people are, Ibbu, Mahundu, Vuruha, Mutikitila, Ngala, Mbalasinte, Ciseke ca banyai, Ioma, Bbwaara, Cizungwe and Iseke.
==Religion== Masubia religion is based on [[ancestor worship]], wherein the deceased ancestors are regarded as guardian spirits. Those who do not honor nor show respects to these spirits are punished. They believe that these spirits have a connection with the Creator, and serve as mediators. According to the [[Joshua Project]], forty percent of the Masubia are Christians while sixty percent practice ethnic religion.<ref>http://www.joshuaproject.net/people-profile.php?peo3=15102&rog3=WA</ref>
==Culture== The Masubia are well known for their vibrant cultural dances known as ''Chiperu'' and ''Chizo'' and their traditional attire, ''Musisi''.<ref>{{cite web|title=People of Caprivi|url=http://www.caprivi.biz/people.html|accessdate=8 October 2012}}</ref>
