{{Anglo-Saxon society}}

The study of the role of [[women]] in particular in the society of [[Anglo-Saxon England]] has been a topic of academic research in history and [[gender studies]] since the 1980s. A seminal study was published by  [[Christine Fell]] as ''Women in Anglo-Saxon England'' in 1984. According to Fell, women were "near equal companions to the males in their lives, such as husbands and brothers, much more than in any other era before modern time".{{sfn|Fell|1987}}{{sfn|Stenton|1990}} Despite this sense of equality in some strata of society, Anglo Saxon women were still subject to [[concubinage]].<!-- This equal status prevailed until the [[Norman Conquest]] of 1066, at which point a military society re-envisioned women as unimportant.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}{{sfn|Stenton|1990}}-->
Gender was influenced by social status, religion and sexuality.{{sfn|Pasternack|2003}}{{clarify|date=November 2014}}<!--what does this even mean and how is it not a universal tautology?-->
They were not only allowed to have private influence, but also a wide liberty of intervention in public affairs.{{sfn|Stenton|1990}}

== Occupations ==
Women and children were generally involved in tasks that required little physical work. Though, due to climate and weather constraints, women may have done the work that needed attention at the time.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}{{clarify|date=November 2014}}<!--the bibliography has 1984-->
{{page needed|date=November 2014}} While men were ox-herders, labourers, swine-herders, and so forth, women were cheese-makers<ref name="Carol Hough 1999">Carol Hough (1999)</ref> and dairy-maids.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} They were also bakers, though not cooks. In [[Old English]] the word for cook is ''coc'', and is only found in the masculine form, while ''baecere'' and ''bascestre'' respectively represent the feminine and masculine forms of baker.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}{{sfn|Hough|1999}} Female slaves were corn-grinders, serving maids, wet-nurses, weavers, and seamstresses.{{sfn|Hough|1999}} Common free women may have been found spinning as well as weaving.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} Women and ladies, including queens, would serve drinks for company and family. This was not only a job for a woman of lower-class,{{sfn|Fell|1987}} though it would have likely been done by a low-class woman if one were present. Women of this time were also entertainers, comedians, and singers, and may have been employed by households or travelling groups.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}

== Christianity ==

Churches in Anglo-Saxon England stressed doctrines that preached about virginity as a virtue and faithful monogamy; this is believed to have limited an individual’s chances of acquiring status, political power and property.{{sfn|Pasternack|2003}} Anglo-Saxon England was the first place in history that women had been raised to [[saint]]hood, and this was the strongest immediately following the acceptance of Christianity.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} Christianity provided lots of freedom for women. It helped them become powerful in society.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holt Literature Language Arts|last=|first=|publisher=Holt Rinehart and Winston|year=2003|isbn=0-03-056498-0|location=Houston, Texas|pages=12}}</ref> Within the church women appeared to have been equal as well there are evidences of anti-feminism found in Homilies.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} Although anti-feminism was found in Homilies, it does not seem to hold true in practice.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} Women who went into the convent and took vows of [[poverty, chastity and obedience]] were glorified in the eyes of the Church and its Fathers.{{sfn|Fredrick Ide|1983}} The convent offered self-development and social responsibility to women, something that women are fighting for today.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} Uniquely, the Anglo-Saxon church had institutions that consisted of male and female monasteries, located together but segregated, and in these the female abbot had the headship of the institution.  Convents were run by abbesses, and this was an opportunity for women to have a position of authority.{{sfn|Hough|1999}} They were responsible for the finances and managing the property, with some the help of the other nuns.<ref name="Carol Hough 1999">Carol Hough (1999)</ref> This control that women had did not survive the Viking invasion of 789,{{sfn|Blair|1984}} although women continued to play a major role in the church in late Anglo-Saxon England.{{sfn|Hough|1999}} Single gendered convents and monasteries had the chores that were commonly done by the other sex would have been performed by the common sex in that location; examples are men would have worked in the kitchens of monasteries and women would have worked in the gardens of nunneries.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}

It is clear that there were equal opportunities for men and women in the Christian Church in Anglo-Saxon England, but it is still important to look at the "Patriarchs of the Bible."{{sfn|Pasternack|2003}} Although women were given these opportunities it is crucial that they were given them by men and that the Church's significant positions of authority were held by men. Thus the gender differences and coping with the ideological conflicts that have to do with sexuality and kinship resulted from the introduction of Christianity.{{sfn|Pasternack|2003}}

== Marriage and divorce ==
In Anglo-Saxon England, there were many laws related to marriage.<ref name="Carol Hough 1999">Carol Hough (1999)</ref> Some historians{{which?|date=May 2016}} profess that the law that neither widow, nor maiden was forced to marry a man that she disliked as being a sign of equality; however, Aethelberht's law contradicts this in as much as a man is legally allowed to steal another man's wife as long as he pays him reparation.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} Once married, a woman was to situate herself as the object of her husband's subjectivity, she was to become the object of his protection and the property, although she still remained the owner of her property.{{sfn|Pasternack|2003}} The Church saw that married women had no authority and were to stand under the lordship of men. Therefore, under the church they were not able to teach, witness, take an oath, nor be a judge.{{sfn|Fredrick Ide|1983}} In marriage, a male often developed his sphere of influence through his wife.{{sfn|Pasternack|2003}} Although women were seen as such under the church, there were laws that protected them in the public sphere when married. Divorce was rare, and the only documented ones were in times of adultery.{{sfn|Hough|1999}} A woman that commits adultery by sleeping with a man that was not her husband while he was still alive was subject to give what she owned to her husband.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} [[Ethelred the Unready|Æthelraed]]'s 1008 code states that widows shall remain unmarried for 12 months after the death of her husband, at which point they have the freedom to choose.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} This was likely the case to allow for the widows have time to think and not make any rash decisions which may have led to relationships or commitments.

A prospective husband had to offer his wife a valuable gift called the ''morgengifu'', a “morning-gift,” which consisted of paying money or giving land for the ladies’ hand in marriage.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holt Literature and Language Arts, Sixth Course|last=|first=|publisher=Holt, Rinehart, and Winston|year=2003|isbn=0030564980|location=Houston, Texas|pages=12}}</ref> This was paid to her directly and she had the right to do with it as she pleased. It is made clear that the marriage finances were held by both man and woman. A woman was free to leave a marriage, keeping in mind the only times divorce was documented in cases of adultery; and if the woman did leave and take the children, she was entitled to half the property.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} These gifts were substantial sums and generally property.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}<ref name="Carol Hough 1999">Carol Hough (1999)</ref> The gifts given by the groom were sometimes viewed as a sale of the bride, when, in actuality, it was to safeguard her interests and add security.{{sfn|Hough|1999}}

== Sexual mores ==
According to the church sexual desires were evil and sinful, thus appeared as so; therefore women were not to enjoy sex.{{sfn|Fredrick Ide|1983}} Many times sex was not gentle, because it was a sense of security for the man and not meant to please the woman.{{sfn|Fredrick Ide|1983}} When it came to paying for sex with a woman belonging to the King she would have cost roughly 30 shillings, while a commoner only 6 shillings.<ref name="Shari Horner 2004">Shari Horner (2004)</ref> The transfer of money for sex shows that there was the presence of prostitution, although it is not clearly stated whether the women condoned the act or not, and this issue is still up for debate; what is known is that there was a sex trade in some form.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}<ref name="Shari Horner 2004" /> The fact that rape of a slave was more expensive than seduction of a free woman shows how rape was viewed so negatively in society, although the law protected women against both actions.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} Laws of [[King Alfred|Ælfred]] go into great detail regarding laws about sexual assaults.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} An example of the law committed by a man was [[Æthelbald of Mercia|King Æthebald]] of Mercia who was punished for numerous reasons, including violating holy nuns who were virgins consecrated to God.{{sfn|Pasternack|2003}} When compensation was paid a free woman, [[churl|ceorl]] or ranked above, she collected the money directly, and the money for slaves went to their owner.  It is also unclear as to whether the wife or husband received the money for their servants.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}<ref name="Carol Hough 1999">Carol Hough (1999)</ref> Rape as a topic is important because it relates to gender relations, class status, property rights, judicial customs, female agency, religious virtues of integrity of the body and representation in of all of these in a society.<ref name="Shari Horner 2004" /> Sexual assaults were greatly penalized whether it was a slave or free woman.{{sfn|Hough|1999}} Burials suggest that a raped body was unceremonious.<ref name="Dawn Hadley 2004">Dawn Hadley (2004)</ref> A few documents suggest that some men of this era applauded other men who beat their wives and that some men even thought that a wife should be beaten regularly; this may have been condoned by clergy.{{sfn|Fredrick Ide|1983}} Even though there were laws protecting women that had been raped, sometimes the acts went unpunished for lack of information or time. The victim herself may not have told  anyone until many years after, or no one really took an interest in the crime if the victim was of the serving class.{{sfn|Fredrick Ide|1983}}

Sex and rape were also found in literature.<ref name="Shari Horner 2004" /><ref name="Dawn Hadley 2004" /> There are actual and threatened acts of violent sexual assaults present in some literature and legal texts;<ref name="Shari Horner 2004">Shari Horner (2004)</ref><ref name="Dawn Hadley 2004" /> an example is the homily of Wulfstan, a text in which he wrote about women being raped at the hands of the Vikings.<ref name="Shari Horner 2004" />

== Laws ==
The written law only represents a portion of the laws that impacted the lives of women; therefore they only reflect partial views of what actually happened.<ref>Mary P Richards and B. Jane Stanfield. (1990)</ref> Despite what the churches doctrines taught, women were considered to be a member of the state and their rights were protected, regardless of their status as maiden, widow or wife.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} Women were classed as oath worthy and could appear as grantors, grantees and witnesses of [[Anglo-Saxon charters|charters]].<ref name="Carol Hough 1999">Carol Hough (1999)</ref> Women were held responsible and accountable under the law for their activity, although were not held accountable for any criminal activity that her husband did, unless she was a willing accessory to the crime.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}{{sfn|Hough|1999}} Along with being law abiding, they received appropriate compensation for crimes that were committed against them, and the compensation was paid directly to them.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}

==Wills==
Women had property rights and many landowners were women.<ref name="Carol Hough 1999">Carol Hough (1999)</ref> They were able to bequeath land, as shown in numerous wills. Leaving property by means of a will was not restricted to kin; it could also be left to servants, religious figures, and churches.{{sfn|Stenton|1990}} Documents of wills and charters show that women owned estates, by virtue of grant, will, or inheritance, and that they were seen roughly equal in the common life of the countryside.{{sfn|Stenton|1990}}{{sfn|Hough|1999}} Evidence in these documents shows no preference to daughters or sons as heirs.<ref name="Carol Hough 1999">Carol Hough (1999)</ref> [[churl|Ceorl]] women and others of high rank were responsible for their homes.<ref>Hough, Carol. "Women." The Blackwell Encyclopedia of Anglo-Saxon England. Ed. Lapidge et al. 1999. 485-487.</ref> Some of the items that women would commonly receive via trust or inheritance were real property estates, slaves, livestock, household furnishings, clothing, jewels, and books.{{sfn|Hough|1999}} Items such as table clothes, bed sheets, and wall hangings were considered women's property because women made them.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}

== Health ==
Anglo-Saxons had warnings for pregnant women, including avoiding foods that were too salty or sweet, pork, and other fatty foods. They were also told to abstain from strong alcohol and too much drink and to avoid travel on horseback.{{sfn|Fell|1987}} If a woman were to stop menstruating supposedly due to a lack of nutrients and was not pregnant, she was to take hot baths, drink hot herb teas, and dress warmly.{{sfn|Fell|1987}}

